correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBeta-adrenergic stimulation in atrial muscle results in \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased contractility\u003C/strong\u003E, one of the key effects of sympathetic nervous system activation on the heart.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe options for \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased contractility\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased conduction velocity\u003C/strong\u003E are incorrect, as beta-adrenergic stimulation generally increases contractility and conduction velocity in cardiac tissue. Other effects of beta-adrenergic stimulation include \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased conduction velocity\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly in the SA and AV nodes, enhancing the speed of electrical impulse propagation, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased pacemaker rate\u003C/strong\u003E, as beta-adrenergic stimulation raises the firing rate of the sinoatrial (SA) node, which is the heart\u0027s natural pacemaker. Therefore, it\u0027s important to note that while increased pacemaker rate is a correct effect of beta-adrenergic stimulation, the question specifically asks about the effect on atrial muscle, making increased contractility the most appropriate answer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Beta-adrenergic stimulation in atrial muscle increases contractility, conduction velocity, and pacemaker rate."],"references":["Skeberdis VA, Gendviliene V, Zablockaite D, Treinys R, Macianskiene R, Bogdelis A, Jurevicius J, Fischmeister R. beta3-adrenergic receptor activation increases human atrial tissue contractility and stimulates the L-type Ca2+ current. J Clin Invest. 2008 Sep;118(9):3219-27. doi: 10.1172/JCI32519. PMID: 18704193; PMCID: PMC2515379.","Woo AY, Xiao RP. \u03b2-Adrenergic receptor subtype signaling in heart: from bench to bedside. Acta Pharmacol Sin. 2012 Mar;33(3):335-41. doi: 10.1038/aps.2011.201. Epub 2012 Jan 30. PMID: 22286918; PMCID: PMC4077138.","Tortora, G. J., Derrickson, B., 